{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526709"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:24:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:24:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14150"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14150"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.37,0.04,0.05,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55828"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6833"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41374"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"2874"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3724"},{"type":"tags","id":"3773"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39626"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55828"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe abdominal pain, headache, and shortness of breath. She has a medical history of systemic lupus erythematosus diagnosed two years ago. Her regular medications include hydroxychloroquine and prednisolone. She does not take any other medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and distressed. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals diffuse tenderness and guarding. Neurological examination shows mild confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 90 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 80 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 180 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 250 U/L (5-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 1.8 (0.8-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ED-dimer: \u0026gt;5000 ng/mL (\u0026lt;500)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EANCA: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT scan of the abdomen shows multiple areas of infarction in the liver and spleen. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT head shows multiple small infarcts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lupus flare with multi-organ involvement","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Septic shock","Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody-associated vasculitis","Catastrophic antiphospholipid syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecatastrophic antiphospholipid syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (CAPS). CAPS is a rare but life-threatening condition characterised by rapid, multi-organ thrombosis, often occurring in patients with underlying autoimmune diseases such as systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of multi-organ involvement (abdominal pain, headache, shortness of breath), along with laboratory findings (thrombocytopenia, elevated creatinine, elevated liver enzymes, and markedly elevated D-dimer) and imaging results (multiple infarcts in liver, spleen, and brain) are all consistent with CAPS. The rapid onset and severity of symptoms, coupled with the patient\u0027s history of SLE, further support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elupus flare with multi-organ involvement\u003C/strong\u003E could present similarly, but the presence of multiple infarcts in different organs and the rapid-onset is more characteristic of CAPS. While lupus can cause organ dysfunction, it typically does not cause such widespread thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E (DIC) can present with similar laboratory findings, including thrombocytopenia and elevated INR. Unlike CAPS, DIC is associated with an underlying systemic disorder (often infection or malignancy) which is not evident in this case. Additionally, the multiple organ infarcts are more characteristic of CAPS than DIC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E could explain some of the clinical features, such as hypotension and tachycardia. However, the presence of multiple infarcts in different organs and the patient\u0027s history of SLE make CAPS a more likely diagnosis. Septic shock would typically present with more overt symptoms of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody-associated vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E (ANCA-associated vasculitis) is unlikely given the negative ANCA result. Moreover, while ANCA-associated vasculitis can cause multi-organ involvement, it typically does not cause the widespread thrombosis seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of CAPS typically involves a combination of anticoagulation, high-dose corticosteroids, and either plasma exchange or intravenous immunoglobulins. Early recognition and aggressive treatment are crucial for improving outcomes in patients with this rare (affects ~1% of individuals with antiphospholipid syndrome) but potentially fatal condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Catastrophic antiphospholipid syndrome is characterised by rapid, multi-organ thrombosis and often presents in a severe, life-threatening fashion.","Treatment for catastrophic antiphospholipid syndrome typically involves a combination of anticoagulation, corticosteroids, and plasma exchange or intravenous immunoglobulins.","Early recognition and aggressive treatment of catastrophic antiphospholipid syndrome is crucial for improving patient outcomes."],"references":["Aguiar CL, Erkan D. Catastrophic antiphospholipid syndrome: how to diagnose a rare but highly fatal disease. Therapeutic Advances in Musculoskeletal Disease. 2013 Dec 1;5(6):305\u201314. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3836378/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41374"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14150"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41374"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:43:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:44:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6833"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55828"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null